text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!SignLanguage]]%0a%0a!Expansion and Standardization of CSL %0a%0a:Author: angelaw%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aA brief history and discussion of Chinese Sign Language %0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aThe earliest records of the existence of a Chinese Sign Language (CSL) date all the way back to the Tang dynasty more than a thousand years ago. Records show although there was no form of standardized sign language during that time, people were still able to communicate through the use of hand gestures. However, widespread use and acceptance of an official CSL did not really come about until the 20th century. This came about after the newly established National Language Reform Committee decided to standardized spoken Chinese first. %0a%0aOver the years, standardized alphabets have been released, but no official lexicon. Individual regions of China have developed their own dialects of CSL with lack of a central, standard language to use. One speaker of CSL notes that when traveling to Shanghai, she couldn't even understand what the Shanghainese CSL speaker was signing. Due to the population and diversity of languages and culture within China, this has often been the case even with spoken languages. %0a%0aIn 2018, after seven years of research, the China's State Language Commission has finally released an official list of 5,000 common Chinese words in standard CSL. This development will undoubtedly work wonders for bridging divides between speakers of various CSL dialects, bringing awareness to those with hearing disabilities, and helping us all feel more connected.%0a%0aSources: %0ahttps://news.cgtn.com/news/2019-09-23/IDSL-China-s-sign-language-history-dates-back-to-Tang-Dynasty-period-KamfGp0Q1y/index.html%0ahttps://www.whatsonweibo.com/chinese-sign-language-online/%0a%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210509-030914-7900#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Additional Information on CSL %0a-> - MarkC%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aDeaf children/people in China face heavy stigma and prejudice. With over 20 million deaf people in China, that's a large group. The Chinese education system has heavily discouraged the use of CSL for almost half a century. However, acceptance of the language is slowly growing.%0a%0aThe two main dialects of CSL is Southern CSL influenced by French Sign Language and Northern CSL influenced by American Sign Language. In CSL, there is an alphabetic system contrasted to written Chinese which did not originally have an alphabet (although pinyin was later introduced).%0a%0aSources:%0a%0ahttps://www.k-international.com/blog/different-types-of-sign-language-around-the-world/%0a%0ahttps://ltl-xian.com/chinese-sign-language/#chapter-2%0a%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210509-030914-7900#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: F:)%0a(:Category: SignLanguage:)
